\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Definition (Locally continuous linear operator)
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Consider to Banach spaces 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
There exists an infinite sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\{u_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 which is contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $D(T)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\{u_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 converges to 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{0}$
\end_inset

 in the norm of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, namely 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bigl\Vert u_{n}-u_{0}\bigr\Vert\rightarrow0\quad(n\rightarrow\infty)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The image of the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\{T(u_{n})\}$
\end_inset

 converges to 
\begin_inset Formula $T(u_{0})$
\end_inset

 in the norm of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bigl\Vert T(u_{n})-T(u_{0})\bigr\Vert\rightarrow0,\quad(n\rightarrow\infty)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The definition requires 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 to be Banach spaces to ensure convergence 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigl\Vert u_{n}-u_{0}\bigr\Vert$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigl\Vert T(u_{n})-T(u_{0})\bigr\Vert$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Continuity means that local convergence at a specific point is preserved
 before and after the mapping 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Definition (Continuous linear operator)
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is locally continuous at everywhere in 
\begin_inset Formula $D(T)$
\end_inset

, we say that 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is continuous linear operator 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsubsection
Definition of bounded operator 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Definition (Bounded Operator)
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
An operator that maps one Banach space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 onto another Banach space 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
bounded 
\series default
if for any 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in D(T)$
\end_inset

, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $M>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bigl\Vert T(u)\bigr\Vert_{Y}\leq M\bigl\Vert u\bigr\Vert_{X}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The boundedness of an operator 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 indicates that the image of 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $T(u)$
\end_inset

 is not jumping out of place extremely far away from the zero element in
 
\begin_inset Formula $R(T)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Boundedness has no relation to linearity 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Definition (Operator norm)
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula $X\mapsto Y$
\end_inset

 be a continuous linear operator.
 Its operator norm is defined by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bigl\Vert T\bigr\Vert=\frac{\bigl\Vert T(u)\bigr\Vert_{y}}{\bigl\Vert u\bigr\Vert_{x}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\bigl\Vert T\bigr\Vert<\infty$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is bounded on the domain 
\begin_inset Formula $D(T)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Equivalence between continuity and boundedness 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Concept of boundedness and continuity become equivalent if the operator
 is linear 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Continuous linear operators are bounded
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Bounded linear operator are continuous 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is continuous 
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow T$
\end_inset

 is locally continuous at 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is bounded
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is bounded 
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow T$
\end_inset

 is globally continuous 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Hence, for linear operator we have an equivalence between local and global
 continuity 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Artificial downscale of operator domain 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Preferably we want to deal with continuous operators 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
What can we do if we encounter a linear operator that is not bounded
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We can scale down its domain in order for it to be bounded 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 be a non-bounded operator whose domain is entirely over an infinite-dimensional
 vector space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Artificially pick up finite number of elements 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},\ldots,x_{n}$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Every linear operator on finite-dimensional space is bounded 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Make 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 bounded by downscale domain of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{n}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Preparation toward eigenvalue like problem 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Solving eigenvalue problem is the central topic in elementary linear algebra
 that deals in infinite-dimensional vector spaces 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For a linear operator in function space, it is generally impossible to establish
 notion of eigenvalues and eigenvectors 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Expand concept using the proportionality relation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Tx=\alpha x
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Infinite-dimensional vector spaces generally do not possess elements 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 that satisfy the above relation 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Look for 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 that makes 
\begin_inset Formula $T-\alpha I$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
invertible 
\series default
which means that there exists a operator 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{-1}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{-1}T=TT^{-1}=I$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The set of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 for which we can find 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is called 
\series bold
spectrum 
\series default
of the operator 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
completely 
\series default
continuous, then the spectrum behaves similar to finite-dimensional matrices
 
\end_layout

