\begin_layout Subsubsection
Compactness or non-compact
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Compactness is important when we look at eigenvalue problems in infinite-dimensi
ons 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Compactness is a generalization of the closedness in Euclidean space, i.e.
 all finite points lie in a certain finite distance to each other 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Suppose a infinite sequence of points is contained in a space
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We extract infinite sub sequence from the original sequence under the condition
 that the sub sequence must converge to a point in the space considered
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $S=\{(z_{1},z_{2},\ldots,z_{n}):\,\bigl|z_{1}\bigr|^{2}+\ldots+\bigl|z_{n}\bigr|^{2}=1\}$
\end_inset

 is compact, because a converging subsequence can be picked up from arbitrary
 infinite point sequences in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This is not possible in infinite dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $S=\{x:\bigl\Vert x\bigr\Vert=1\}$
\end_inset

 is not compact 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Infinite-dimensional spaces are not closed but open to infinitely many direction
s.
 Subsequences that extracted from an infinite sequence may not be convergent
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Why is 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 not compact, although 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{c}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is compact 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{e_{1},e_{2},\ldots\}$
\end_inset

 be an orthonormal basis of the space 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bigl\Vert e_{m}-e_{n}\bigr\Vert^{2}=\bigl\Vert e_{m}\bigr\Vert^{2}-(e_{n},e_{m})-(e_{m},e_{n})+\bigl\Vert e_{n}\bigr\Vert^{2}=2
\]

\end_inset

from which follows 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigl\Vert e_{m}-e_{n}\bigr\Vert^{2}=\sqrt{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We can find infinitely many sequences of points on 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 in which all pairs of point in the sequence are apart by 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
There exists on 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 an infinite number of points all of which equi-separated.
 Not matter what subsequence are picked from the original sequence 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The subsequence does not longer be convergent 
\end_layout

